rization of US domestic and foreign affairs was the product of America’s failure in Vietnam. Unsettled by their inability to prevail in Southeast Asia, US leaders increasingly came to see a host of problems as immune to political solutions. Rather, crime, drugs, and terrorism were enemies spawned in “badlands”—whether the Middle East or stateside inner cities. Characterized as sites of endemic violence, badlands lay beyond the pale of civilization, their ostensibly racially and culturally alien inhabitants best handled by force.Yet militarized policy has brought few victories. Its failures—in Iraq, Afghanistan, US cities, and increasingly rural and borderland America—have only served to reinforce fears of weakness. It is time, Khalil argues, for a new approach. Instead of managing never-ending conflicts, we need to reinvest in the tools of traditional politics and diplomacy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aDrug controlxHistoryy20th century. 0aDrug controlxHistoryy21st century. 0aWar on Terrorism, 2001-2009. 7aHISTORY / Military / Wars & Conflicts (Other).2bisacsh  abill clinton.  acold war.  acounterinsurgency.  acounterterrorism.  ageorge h w bush.  ahenry kissinger.  aintelligence services.  anarcotics.  aobama.  apolice brutality.  apopular culture.  arichard nixon.  aronald reagan.  aseptember 11.  asurveillance.  atrump.  aukraine.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311074971740uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674296886?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674296886423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674296886/original  a978-3-11-074971-7  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles